This is a surprisingly deep question because “location” didn’t disappear online—it fragmented into many different kinds of terrain.

In real estate, location determines:

* Who walks by.
* How much trust exists.
* What neighbors surround you.
* How expensive attention is.
* Whether people return.

The internet has all of those too. They’re just invisible.

For Wild Hawg and Pantheon, I’d think about Digital Geography.

Instead of one location, you occupy many layers simultaneously.

Layer 1 — Search Terrain

This is Google, AI search, Amazon search, App Store search, YouTube search.

Equivalent:
Prime retail shelf.

Goal:
Own the answer whenever someone asks a question you solve.

Example:

“I need energy”

“I want healthy gummies”

“How do I learn AI?”

Pantheon should eventually become part of those answer pathways.

⸻

Layer 2 — Social Terrain

TikTok
Instagram
X
Reddit
Discord
LinkedIn

These are cities.

Each has different cultures.

Don’t copy content.

Adapt to the terrain.

Like animals evolving differently on islands.

⸻

Layer 3 — Algorithm Terrain

People often optimize for audiences.

Algorithms decide audiences.

Understand:

Recommendation engines

Ranking systems

Watch time

Shares

Search intent

Retention

This becomes digital zoning law.

⸻

Layer 4 — Trust Terrain

This one is huge.

Every recommendation system estimates trust.

Signals include:

Reviews

Replies

Backlinks

Mentions

Repeat customers

Authority

Community

Trust compounds like owning property in a neighborhood that becomes more desirable over time.

⸻

Layer 5 — Community Terrain

Communities are neighborhoods.

Examples:

Reddit

Discord

Facebook Groups

Slack communities

Forums

People already gather.

You don’t always need to build a city.

Sometimes you become the favorite shop inside an existing one.

⸻

Layer 6 — Semantic Terrain

This one gets interesting.

LLMs don’t think in webpages.

They think in semantic neighborhoods.

Words that occur together become neighbors.

Eventually you want:

Wild Hawg

Energy

Military

Performance

Adventure

Healthy snacks

Natural fuel

…to occupy nearby semantic space.

Pantheon should likewise become semantically adjacent to ideas like agentic AI, cognitive architecture, knowledge systems, and human–AI collaboration through consistent, high-quality work.

⸻

Layer 7 — Attention Terrain

Some places have heavy traffic.

Others have highly qualified traffic.

Millions of random visitors aren’t necessarily better than a thousand highly interested ones.

Attention has both quantity and quality.

⸻

Layer 8 — Memory Terrain

This is where brands become landmarks.

People remember:

Nike

LEGO

Apple

Not because they appear once.

Because they occupy stable mental real estate.

Memory is probably the scarcest land online.

⸻

Layer 9 — AI Terrain

This is emerging now.

Instead of users browsing…

AI agents browse.

Your future customer might ask an assistant:

“Find me an energy gummy that doesn’t crash.”

or

“Teach me agentic AI.”

The “storefront” increasingly becomes whether AI systems can discover, understand, and accurately represent your brand. That favors clear documentation, structured information, authoritative content, and consistent messaging.

⸻

So do we find the terrain or craft it?

Both.

Think of three strategies:

1. Prospect

* Find underdeveloped, high-potential spaces before competitors notice them.

2. Build

* Improve the places you occupy with content, products, community, and trust.

3. Terraform

* Create entirely new categories or mental models that others begin using.

The most enduring companies often move from prospecting to building and, occasionally, to terraforming.

⸻

A Pantheon daemon: Cartographer

This seems like a capability your framework doesn’t explicitly name yet.

Mission

Map the digital world continuously.

Questions

Where are people gathering?

Where is attention flowing?

Where is trust forming?

Where are semantic neighborhoods expanding?

Where are competitors absent?

Where are algorithms shifting?

Where is the cost of attention dropping?

Where are AI systems increasingly citing or retrieving information?

Outputs

* Opportunity maps
* Competitive heat maps
* Semantic maps
* Trust maps
* Community maps
