⸻

One more layer: Location is becoming “Position”

The internet is gradually shifting from pages to relationships.

A useful abstraction is:

Position = Location × Reputation × Relationships × Timing

You can rank highly and still fail if people don’t trust you.

You can have a great reputation but remain invisible if you’re hard to discover.

You can have both but miss the moment.

For Wild Hawg, the goal is to become the obvious answer in the mental neighborhood of clean, performance-oriented energy gummies.

For Pantheon, the goal is to become associated with a distinctive body of work around AI architecture, knowledge organization, and human–AI collaboration. That position is earned over time through consistent artifacts, open discussion, and demonstrated usefulness rather than by naming alone.

Viewed this way, digital “location” is less like owning a single storefront and more like cultivating an ecosystem. The strongest position isn’t just a spot on the map—it becomes a destination that search engines, recommendation systems, AI assistants, and people all learn to navigate toward.